  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. A classical particle rolling downhill never bounces backward. A quantum wave hitting the same downward potential step can split, with part reflected even though both sides are allowed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why can a quantum particle reflect from a downward potential step when both sides are classically allowed?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — STEP REFLECTION",
            "segment": "Reflection Without a Forbidden Region",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "matching waves across the boundary…",
            "output": [
              "The wavelength changes abruptly.",
              "Boundary matching creates reflection."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.95,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Classically, lower potential means greater kinetic energy. The particle speeds up and continues right. There is no turning point and no reason to reverse.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.7,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "So what can possibly send a quantum wave back?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.11,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "On the left, the wave number is k one. On the lower-potential right, the same total energy gives more kinetic energy and a larger wave number k two, so the wavelength becomes shorter.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "morph"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The wave function and its derivative must join continuously at the boundary. One incoming wave alone cannot match a transmitted wave with a different wavelength and slope.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "match"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.9,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The solution adds a reflected wave on the left. Incoming plus reflected amplitudes supply exactly the boundary value and slope needed by the transmitted wave.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "split"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.11,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "For an abrupt step, the reflected amplitude is k one minus k two over k one plus k two. The reflected probability is its magnitude squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.41,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "If the two wave numbers nearly match, reflection is tiny. Increase the mismatch, and the reflected fraction grows. The boundary behaves like an impedance change for waves.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.94,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Nothing is classically forbidden here. Both k values are real, and the transmitted wave propagates. Reflection comes from abrupt matching, not from insufficient energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "qualify"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.07,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Smooth the same potential change over many wavelengths and the wave adapts gradually, so reflection becomes much smaller. Abruptness is the essential ingredient.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.58,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is why a downhill step can reflect while a gently descending ramp scarcely does. Quantum particles inherit the boundary behavior of waves.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "map"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.53,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Enough energy does not guarantee zero reflection. A sudden wavelength mismatch splits the wave, even across a potential drop.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:37:45"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. If k two equals two k one, compute the reflected probability from the step formula, then predict what smoothing the step does.",
      "shot": {
